04678nam a22007575i 9780228007654DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280076547 a10.1515/97802280076542doi  a(DE-B1597)657081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPG3458.Z9bC42 2021 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a891.73/32231 aPeterson, Nadya L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChekhov's Children :bContext and Text in Late Imperial Russia /cNadya L. Peterson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b3 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- tThe Child in Chekhov’s Time -- tThe Child Imagined: The Literary Canon -- tThe Humanization Project: Pro/Contra -- tThe Child Examined: Pedagogical Psychology -- tThe Child in Chekhov -- tThe Emergence of Language: The Writer and the Child -- tThe Child’s Text -- tKids at Play -- tFarewell to Childhood: The Steppe -- tThe Afterchildhood -- tConclusion: The Anxiety of Ignorance -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnton Chekhov's representations of children have generally remained on the periphery of scholarly attention. Yet his stories about children, which focus on communication and the emergence of personhood, also illuminate the process by which the author forged his own language of expression and occupy a uniquely important place within his work.Chekhov's Children explores these stories – dating from Chekhov's early writings in the 1880s – as a distinct body of work unified by the theme of maturation and by the creation of a literary model of childhood. Nadya Peterson describes the evolution of Chekhov's model and its connection with the prevalent views on children in the literature, education, medicine, and psychology of his time. As with his later writing, Chekhov's portrayals of young protagonists exhibit complexity, diversity, and a broad reach across the writer's cultural and literary landscape, dealing with such themes as the distinctiveness of a child's perspective, the relationship between the worlds of children and adults, the nature of child development, socialization, gender differences, and sexuality. While reconstructing a particular literary model of childhood, this book brings to light a body of discourse on children, childhood development, and education prominent in Russia in the late nineteenth century.Chekhov's Children accords this topic the significance it deserves by placing Chekhov's model of childhood within the broad context of his time and reassessing established notions about the child's place in the author's oeuvre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChild psychology in literature. 0aChildren in literature. 0aChildrenzRussiaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aChekhov.  aK D Ushinsky.  aLeo Tolstoy.  aRussian education.  aRussian peasant culture.  aS T Aksakov.  aacquisition knowledge.  achild characters.  achild psychology.  achildhood.  acreativity.  adevelopmental psychology.  adramatic sketch.  aearly.  agames.  ahistory.  ahumanities.  ahumor magazines.  aliterature.  amedicine.  apsychology.  ashort stories.  atrauma.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228007654?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007654/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles